Title:
Executing Kernel Routines via Syscall Table Hijack (Windows 11 KiServiceTable)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This repository demonstrates a Windows 11 kernel-mode technique to execute arbitrary existing kernel routines by temporarily hijacking a syscall dispatch entry in `nt!KiServiceTable`.  
- It assumes an initial kernel read/write primitive (demo uses the BYOVD RTCore64 driver) to flip page permissions at the PDE level, overwrite the `NtSetQuotaInformationFile` service-table entry, trigger the syscall, then restore the original entry and protections.  
- The write targets the packed 32-bit SSDT entry format (offset<<4 plus `stackArgs` nibble) and uses a generic user-mode `syscall` stub to call redirected routines with varying arity.  
- Included demos show kernel-assisted process introspection (`PsLookupProcessByProcessId`), token stealing for SYSTEM (`/privesc` via `memcpy`), and toggling PPL by patching `_EPROCESS.Protection` (`/ppl`).  
- The write-up discusses why this can evade or reduce friction with modern mitigations (KCFG/KCET/W^X/HVCI/VBS) by only calling code already in `ntoskrnl.exe` and performing “data-only” page-table flag changes.  
- It’s primarily useful for kernel exploitation researchers, red teamers with post-exploitation kernel R/W, and defenders studying SSDT tampering and BYOVD tradecraft.

Technical Focus:
- SSDT/KiServiceTable syscall dispatch internals and entry encoding (offset<<4, stackArgs)
- PDE/PTE paging manipulation to bypass read-only mappings (large pages, R/W bit flip)
- Kernel R/W primitives via BYOVD (RTCore64) and reducing IOCTL telemetry
- Redirecting syscalls to exported kernel routines (e.g., `PsLookupProcessByProcessId`, `memcpy`)
- Token manipulation via `_EPROCESS.Token` (EX_FAST_REF) and PPL via `_EPROCESS.Protection`
- Offset resolution strategies (WinDbg manual offsets vs runtime RVA resolution)

Use Cases:
- Execute chosen `ntoskrnl` routines from user mode by repointing a syscall slot
- Privilege escalation by swapping a process token to SYSTEM
- Modify process protection state (PPL) for tampering or testing protections
- Build a quieter kernel read/write channel after an initial BYOVD bootstrap
- Research/detection engineering for SSDT entry changes and page-table permission flips

Keywords:
Windows 11, kernel exploitation, KiServiceTable, SSDT, syscall hijacking, NtSetQuotaInformationFile, KeServiceDescriptorTableShadow, MiGetPteAddress, PDE, PTE, large page, page table flags, RTCore64, BYOVD, PsLookupProcessByProcessId, EPROCESS, EX_FAST_REF, token stealing, memcpy, PPL, _PS_PROTECTION, WinDbg, IDA Pro, KCFG, KCET, HVCI, VBS, PatchGuard